The Homeric form in this sense is drirA, d. 18. 323 πaida dè de driraAe. The word drAo may have heen sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: Il. 6. 400 raĩd' r xoAr cxou' a Ad- ooa, jroo ares. apoooνv might be acc. in appos. with υiν only; but is better talen as acc. in appos. with the hole sentence (see on El. 130 jxer u xaμr πaoa- μbboν). The conjecture apoooi̊ is no gain. 80 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic olda, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, l. 354. obroi.. uj: ep. 83, 421.
